      "shortest": true,
      "solution": "def hex6(code)\n  return code if code.size > 6\n  return code.gsub(/\\w/, '\\0\\0')\nend\ndef hex3(code)\n  return code if code.size < 6\n  return code.gsub(/(\\w)\\w/, '\\1')\nend\nn = gets.to_i\ncodes = []\nn.times do\n  hex_code = gets.chomp\n  codes << hex_code\nend\nsizes = codes.map(&:size)\nmajority = sizes.count{_1 < 6} > n/2 ? 3 : 6\nout = codes.map{|code| majority == 6 ? hex6(code) : hex3(code) }\nputs out",
      "statement": "CSS colour hex codes are usually written with 6 characters, e.g. {{#00FF55}}. However, you can also use a shorthand with 3 characters, e.g. {{#0F5}}.\n\nYou hate style sheets that are inconsistent in their usage of shorthand, so you've collected all the colours from a style sheet and want to convert all the hex codes to one format (either 3 or 6 characters). You will convert them to whichever is most commonly used and print the consistent results. If both are equally used, then you want them converted to 6 characters.\n\nTo convert from 3 characters to 6, you simply double each character:\n{{#ABC}} → {{#AABBCC}}\n\nTo convert from 6 characters to 3, you simply take the first character of each pair:\n{{#D1E0FF}} → {{#DEF}}",
